United Kingdom","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1135–Abt 1200":"circa 1135–circa 1200","1135–1200":"1135–1200","1139–1184":"1139–1184","1153–1203":"1153–1203","1121–1175":"1121–1175","1095–Male":"1095–Overleden","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1100–Female":"1100–Overleden","1102–1153":"1102–1153","1145–1225":"1145–1225","about 1160":"circa 1160","before 1135":"vóór 1135","1121":"1121","1175":"1175","1153":"1153","1184":"1184","1095":"1095","1160":"1160","12 June 1153":"12 juni 1153","1216":"1216","1139":"1139","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","Abt 1200":"circa 1200","1102":"1102","1135":"1135","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1100":"1100","about 1135":"circa 1135","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Stewkley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Stewkley, Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"en":{"about 1135–Abt 1200":"about 1135–about 1200","1135–1200":"1135–1200","1139–1184":"1139–1184","1153–1203":"1153–1203","1121–1175":"1121–1175","1095–Male":"1095–Deceased","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1100–Female":"1100–Deceased","1102–1153":"1102–1153","1145–1225":"1145–1225","about 1160":"about 1160","before 1135":"before 1135","1121":"1121","1175":"1175","1153":"1153","1184":"1184","1095":"1095","1160":"1160","12 June 1153":"12 June 1153","1216":"1216","1139":"1139","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","Abt 1200":"about 1200","1102":"1102","1135":"1135","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1100":"1100","about 1135":"about 1135","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Stewkley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Stewkley, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Beaumont was born about 1135, in Warwickshire, England, her father, Roger de Beaumont, was 35 and her mother, Gundred de Warenne, was -9. She had at least 1 son with Geoffrey de Clinton. She died about 1200, at the age of 67."},"et":{"about 1135–Abt 1200":"umbes 1135–umbes 1200","1135–1200":"1135–1200","1139–1184":"1139–1184","1153–1203":"1153–1203","1121–1175":"1121–1175","1095–Male":"1095–Surnud","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1102–1153":"1102–1153","1145–1225":"1145–1225","about 1160":"umbes 1160","before 1135":"enne 1135","1121":"1121","1175":"1175","1153":"1153","1184":"1184","1095":"1095","1160":"1160","12 June 1153":"12. juuni 1153","1216":"1216","1139":"1139","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1102":"1102","1135":"1135","1145":"1145","1200":"1200","1100":"1100","about 1135":"umbes 1135","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Stewkley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Stewkley, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, Uni